    <item>
      <title>Bluetti Fast Charging for Van Life: The Recovery-First Guide</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/bluetti-fast-charging/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 22 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/bluetti-fast-charging/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Bluetti Fast Charging for Van Life: The Recovery-First Guide&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;bluetti-fast-charging-for-van-life-the-recovery-first-guide&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#bluetti-fast-charging-for-van-life-the-recovery-first-guide&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In real van life, power stress usually comes from &lt;strong&gt;bad recovery&lt;/strong&gt;, not just low capacity. Heat, humidity, and cloudy stretches expose weak charging plans quickly. That’s why this page focuses on &lt;strong&gt;recovery-first decisions&lt;/strong&gt; instead of spec-sheet hype.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>How to Survive a Cloudy Week in Van Life Without Power Stress</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/cloudy-week-power-recovery-plan/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 22 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/cloudy-week-power-recovery-plan/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;How to Survive a Cloudy Week in Van Life Without Power Stress&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;how-to-survive-a-cloudy-week-in-van-life-without-power-stress&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#how-to-survive-a-cloudy-week-in-van-life-without-power-stress&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A cloudy week exposes your recovery plan, not just your battery size. If refill windows shrink and daily loads stay steady, even a system that felt fine can become stressful fast. The goal is to protect stability, not chase perfect conditions.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Solar Input Explained for Portable Power Stations</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/blog/solar-input-explained-for-power-stations/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 22 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/blog/solar-input-explained-for-power-stations/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Solar input is useful, but it is only reliable when panel sizing, weather assumptions, and charge windows are realistic.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Core Concepts&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;core-concepts&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#core-concepts&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Input limits, panel voltage/current matching, and harvest variability drive outcomes more than headline panel wattage.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Solar vs Alternator Charging for Van Life: Which Builds a More Stable Power Plan?</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/solar-vs-alternator-charging/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 22 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/solar-vs-alternator-charging/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Solar vs Alternator Charging for Van Life: Which Builds a More Stable Power Plan?&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;solar-vs-alternator-charging-for-van-life-which-builds-a-more-stable-power-plan&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#solar-vs-alternator-charging-for-van-life-which-builds-a-more-stable-power-plan&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Most van power failures are &lt;strong&gt;recovery failures&lt;/strong&gt;, not storage failures. You can have enough battery on paper and still feel unstable in real weather. A stable plan is built around how reliably you can refill usable power after hard-use days.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Van Power Planning Mistakes That Cost You Comfort (and Money)</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/van-power-planning-mistakes/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 22 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/van-power-planning-mistakes/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Van Power Planning Mistakes That Cost You Comfort (and Money)&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;van-power-planning-mistakes-that-cost-you-comfort-and-money&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#van-power-planning-mistakes-that-cost-you-comfort-and-money&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Most van power failures are &lt;strong&gt;recovery failures&lt;/strong&gt;, not battery-label failures. You can buy enough capacity on paper and still feel unstable week to week. Heat, humidity, cloud cover, and winter sun angle expose weak plans quickly.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Best Budget Solar for Van Life</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/best-of/van-solar/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 21 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/best-of/van-solar/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;If you want the quick answer: most budget builders should start with a &lt;strong&gt;200W to 400W system&lt;/strong&gt; paired with a battery bank sized for one day of normal use. Oversizing too early is one of the fastest ways to blow a build budget.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
